From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: focused dump on affected CPU +
 per-CPU snapshot recording on all other cores at 3s

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop() when active_load_balance_cpu_stop() triggers a nested
stop_one_cpu_nowait() via:

  finish_task_switch()
    -> run_balance_callbacks()
      -> sched_balance_rq() OR balance_push()
        -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()   <-- re-entrancy while already executing
                                        inside stop_two_cpus / multi_cpu_stop

==========================================================================
Design: focused dump on affected CPU + per-CPU snapshot from all others
==========================================================================

Instead of sending IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE to all cores (trigger_all_cpu_
backtrace), each CPU records its own state into its own percpu slot the
moment it detects the 3s timeout, then one CPU wins dump ownership and
prints everything sequentially.

  EVERY CPU detecting timeout (Phase 1, before cmpxchg):
    stopper_snapshot_self(): writes own percpu stopper_snapshot slot.
    Lockless -- each CPU writes only its own slot, no contention ever.

  ONE CPU wins atomic_cmpxchg (dump owner):
    Full focused dump of itself (Sec1-5: outer fn, msdata, masks,
    own stopper state, own dump_stack).
    Then reads all other CPUs' percpu snapshots (Sec6) sequentially.
    panic() immediately.

  ALL other detecting CPUs (Phase 2 losers):
    Snapshot already written. Spin: while(1) cpu_relax() +
    touch_nmi_watchdog(). Brought down by owner's panic().

==========================================================================
Code placement (critical for Clang 19 build correctness)
==========================================================================

stop_machine.c defines types in this order:
  ~line  28  includes end
  ~line 167  enum multi_stop_state
  ~line 180  struct cpu_stopper  +  DEFINE_PER_CPU(cpu_stopper, ...)
  ~line 210  struct multi_stop_data

Any function that references cpu_stopper (the percpu variable) or
struct cpu_stopper (the type) MUST be placed after ~line 180.
Any function that references struct multi_stop_data MUST be placed
after ~line 210.

This patch adds two insertion points:

  INSERT POINT A -- after includes, before enum multi_stop_state (~line 28):
    - #define STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES
    - static atomic_t stopper_dump_owner
    - struct stopper_cpu_snapshot
    - DEFINE_PER_CPU(stopper_snapshot)
    - stopper_snapshot_self()
    None of these reference cpu_stopper or struct multi_stop_data.
    stopper_snapshot_self() takes fn+caller as plain pointer/ulong
    parameters so it never needs to see struct cpu_stopper.

  INSERT POINT B -- after struct multi_stop_data (~line 210), the
    [FIX-A] location already established by the production patch:
    - stopper_state_names[]
    - state_name() inline helper
    - stopper_dump_one_cpu()     -- uses per_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper, ...)
    - stopper_dump_msdata()      -- uses struct multi_stop_data *
    - stopper_print_other_snapshots() -- reads per_cpu(stopper_snapshot)
    - stopper_deadlock_dump()    -- uses this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper)
    All types fully defined at this point.

==========================================================================
TIMELINE
==========================================================================

  T=0s    deadlock begins

  T=3s    time_after() fires on one or more CPUs at position C.
          Phase 1 (ALL detecting CPUs):
            stopper_snapshot_self(): fills own percpu slot, valid=true.
          Phase 2 (cmpxchg race):
            ONE CPU wins -> stopper_deadlock_dump() -> panic()
            ALL others  -> while(1) cpu_relax() + touch_nmi_watchdog()

  T=3s    Sec1: outer stopper fn + caller  (root cause)   <50ms
  T=3s    Sec2: multi_stop_data state                     <50ms
  T=3s    Sec3: CPU masks                                 <50ms
  T=3s    Sec4: owner CPU stopper state (detailed)        <100ms
  T=3s    Sec5: owner CPU dump_stack()                    ~100ms
  T=3.5s  Sec6: read + print all percpu snapshots         <10ms
                No IPI. No cross-CPU wait. Fully sequential.

  T~3.6s  panic() called. Ramdump captured.
  T=11s   Qualcomm bark_time -- ~7s margin.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'. Clang 19 warns at every call
site via -Wsigned-unsigned-enum-conversion.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Position C unconditional detection (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

  do {
    if (curstate < msdata->state) { ... }
    if (is_active)       ack_state(msdata);         /* A */
    else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
        touch_nmi_watchdog(); rcu_momentary_eqs();  /* B: not in PREPARE */
    }
    /* C: ALL CPUs, ALL states, every iteration */
    if (!timed_out && time_after(...)) { ... }
  } while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);

rcu_momentary_eqs() note: position B is unreachable in PREPARE state
(condition false). IRQs stay ON. jiffies advance. time_after() fires.
In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: IRQs off, jiffies frozen, time_after() false. Safe.

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================

- Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
- No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
- Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible
- No trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() -- removed (IPI, not needed)
- atomic_cmpxchg(): <linux/atomic.h> -- already included
- DEFINE_PER_CPU(): <linux/percpu.h> -- already included
- smp_wmb() / READ_ONCE() / WRITE_ONCE(): unconditionally available

Bug: b/XXXXXXXXX
Change-Id: Ixxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
Signed-off-by: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
---
 kernel/stop_machine.c | 330 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 319 insertions(+), 11 deletions(-)

diff --git a/kernel/stop_machine.c b/kernel/stop_machine.c
index 5d2d056..snapshot2 100644
--- a/kernel/stop_machine.c
+++ b/kernel/stop_machine.c
@@ -10,9 +10,12 @@
 #include <linux/compiler.h>
 #include <linux/completion.h>
 #include <linux/cpu.h>
+#include <linux/cpumask.h>
+#include <linux/jiffies.h>
 #include <linux/init.h>
 #include <linux/kthread.h>
 #include <linux/export.h>
 #include <linux/percpu.h>
+#include <linux/sched/debug.h>
 #include <linux/sched.h>
 #include <linux/stop_machine.h>
 #include <linux/interrupt.h>
@@ -25,6 +28,95 @@
 #include <linux/nmi.h>
 #include <linux/sched/wake_q.h>
 
+/* =========================================================
+ * INSERT POINT A -- before enum multi_stop_state / struct cpu_stopper.
+ *
+ * RULE: nothing here may reference cpu_stopper (the percpu variable)
+ *       or struct cpu_stopper (the type). Both are defined later in
+ *       the file (~line 180). Clang 19 will error on any forward use.
+ *
+ * stopper_snapshot_self() receives fn and caller as plain parameters
+ * (void * and unsigned long) so it never needs struct cpu_stopper.
+ * ========================================================= */
+
+/*
+ * STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES -- jiffies threshold for deadlock detection.
+ *
+ * CONFIG_HZ=250 (target): 3 * 250 = 750 jiffies = 3000ms.
+ * Fires at position C in PREPARE state where IRQs are ON and jiffies
+ * advance at full rate.
+ * In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: IRQs disabled, jiffies frozen, time_after() false.
+ */
+#define STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES  (3 * HZ)
+
+/* Compile-time guard: catches misconfigured HZ before runtime. */
+static_assert(HZ > 0, "HZ must be > 0");
+
+/*
+ * stopper_dump_owner -- atomic guard for single-CPU dump execution.
+ *
+ * -1 = no owner. First CPU to win atomic_cmpxchg becomes the sole dump
+ * owner: runs all diagnostic sections then calls panic(). All other
+ * detecting CPUs spin in while(1) cpu_relax() + touch_nmi_watchdog().
+ */
+static atomic_t stopper_dump_owner = ATOMIC_INIT(-1);
+
+/**
+ * struct stopper_cpu_snapshot - per-CPU state captured at timeout moment
+ *
+ * Written by each CPU into its OWN percpu slot -- no locks, no atomics.
+ * Read by the dump owner sequentially after its own dump sections.
+ *
+ * @cpu:       CPU id of the writing CPU
+ * @curstate:  multi_stop_state at the moment of detection
+ * @is_active: true if this CPU was the fn-running (active) CPU
+ * @fn:        stopper fn at detection -- passed from call site
+ * @caller:    stopper caller -- passed from call site
+ * @elapsed_j: jiffies elapsed since spin entry
+ * @valid:     written LAST (after smp_wmb) -- signals owner to print
+ */
+struct stopper_cpu_snapshot {
+	unsigned int  cpu;
+	int           curstate;
+	bool          is_active;
+	void         *fn;
+	unsigned long caller;
+	unsigned long elapsed_j;
+	bool          valid;
+};
+
+/* One snapshot slot per CPU. Zero-initialised (valid=false) at boot. */
+DEFINE_PER_CPU(struct stopper_cpu_snapshot, stopper_snapshot);
+
+/**
+ * stopper_snapshot_self() - write this CPU's state into its percpu slot
+ * @cpu:       this CPU's id
+ * @curstate:  multi_stop_state at detection
+ * @is_active: true if this is the active (fn-running) CPU
+ * @fn:        stopper fn pointer -- read at call site in multi_cpu_stop()
+ *             where struct cpu_stopper is fully in scope. Passed here as
+ *             void * to avoid any reference to struct cpu_stopper, which
+ *             is not yet defined at INSERT POINT A.
+ * @caller:    stopper caller address -- same reason, passed as ulong
+ * @elapsed_j: jiffies elapsed since spin entry
+ *
+ * Called by ALL CPUs that detect the timeout, BEFORE the cmpxchg.
+ * Writes only to this CPU's own percpu slot -- always safe, no locks.
+ */
+static void stopper_snapshot_self(unsigned int cpu, int curstate,
+				  bool is_active, void *fn,
+				  unsigned long caller,
+				  unsigned long elapsed_j)
+{
+	struct stopper_cpu_snapshot *snap = this_cpu_ptr(&stopper_snapshot);
+
+	snap->cpu       = cpu;
+	snap->curstate  = curstate;
+	snap->is_active = is_active;
+	snap->fn        = fn;
+	snap->caller    = caller;
+	snap->elapsed_j = elapsed_j;
+	/*
+	 * smp_store_release() is the correct pairing for
+	 * smp_load_acquire() in the reader.
+	 *
+	 * It acts as a RELEASE barrier: all writes to snap->* above are
+	 * guaranteed to be visible to any CPU that subsequently observes
+	 * snap->valid == true via smp_load_acquire().
+	 *
+	 * This replaces the smp_wmb() + WRITE_ONCE() pattern which was
+	 * incorrect: WRITE_ONCE alone carries no ordering guarantee, so
+	 * a reader could see valid=true before the payload fields were
+	 * visible, even after smp_wmb() on the writer side.
+	 */
+	smp_store_release(&snap->valid, true);
+}
+
+/* === end INSERT POINT A === */
+
 /*
  * Structure to determine completion condition and record errors. May
  * be shared by works on different cpus.
@@ -195,6 +287,191 @@ struct multi_stop_data {
 	atomic_t thread_ack;
 };
 
+/* =========================================================
+ * INSERT POINT B -- after struct multi_stop_data.
+ *
+ * [FIX-A] All helpers that reference cpu_stopper (the percpu variable),
+ * struct cpu_stopper, or struct multi_stop_data must be placed HERE,
+ * after all three are fully defined. Inserting before any of them
+ * causes Clang 19 [-Werror,-Wvisibility] or "undeclared identifier".
+ * ========================================================= */
+
+/*
+ * stopper_state_names[] -- human-readable multi_stop_state names.
+ * Designated-initialiser constants require enum multi_stop_state in scope.
+ * struct multi_stop_data must be defined before dump helpers below use it.
+ */
+static const char * const stopper_state_names[] = {
+	[MULTI_STOP_NONE]        = "NONE",
+	[MULTI_STOP_PREPARE]     = "PREPARE",
+	[MULTI_STOP_DISABLE_IRQ] = "DISABLE_IRQ",
+	[MULTI_STOP_RUN]         = "RUN",
+	[MULTI_STOP_EXIT]        = "EXIT",
+};
+static_assert(ARRAY_SIZE(stopper_state_names) == MULTI_STOP_EXIT + 1,
+	"stopper_state_names[] out of sync with enum multi_stop_state");
+
+static inline const char *stopper_state_name(int s)
+{
+	return ((unsigned int)s < ARRAY_SIZE(stopper_state_names) &&
+		stopper_state_names[s])
+		? stopper_state_names[s] : "UNKNOWN";
+}
+
+/* -----------------------------------------------------------------------
+ * Dump helpers -- noinline, called only from the panic path (one CPU).
+ * All placed at INSERT POINT B where cpu_stopper and multi_stop_data
+ * are fully defined.
+ * ----------------------------------------------------------------------- */
+
+/**
+ * stopper_dump_one_cpu() - print this CPU's stopper state to dmesg
+ * @cpu: the dump-owner CPU
+ *
+ * Lockless read of cpu_stopper -- intentional on the panic path.
+ * Only called for the owner CPU (the affected core), not all CPUs.
+ * Other CPUs' data comes from their stopper_snapshot percpu slots.
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_dump_one_cpu(unsigned int cpu)
+{
+	/* cpu_stopper: struct cpu_stopper, DEFINE_PER_CPU -- defined above */
+	struct cpu_stopper *st = per_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper, cpu);
+	struct cpu_stop_work *w;
+	int n = 0;
+
+	pr_emerg("  task=%-16s enabled=%d\n",
+		 st->thread ? st->thread->comm : "(null)",
+		 st->enabled);
+	pr_emerg("  fn=%pS  caller=%pS\n",
+		 st->fn, (void *)st->caller);
+
+	list_for_each_entry(w, &st->works, list) {
+		pr_emerg("  pending[%d]: fn=%pS caller=%pS\n",
+			 n++, w->fn, (void *)w->caller);
+		if (n >= 8) {
+			pr_emerg("  ... (truncated at 8)\n");
+			break;
+		}
+	}
+	if (!n)
+		pr_emerg("  pending works: (none)\n");
+}
+
+/**
+ * stopper_dump_msdata() - print multi_stop_data fields to dmesg
+ * @msdata:    shared state machine data -- struct multi_stop_data defined above
+ * @owner_cpu: dump-owner CPU id
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_dump_msdata(struct multi_stop_data *msdata,
+					 unsigned int owner_cpu)
+{
+	int state = READ_ONCE(msdata->state);
+
+	pr_emerg("=== Sec2: multi_stop_data (owner CPU%u) ===\n", owner_cpu);
+	pr_emerg("  state       : %d (%s)\n", state, stopper_state_name(state));
+	pr_emerg("  num_threads : %u\n", msdata->num_threads);
+	pr_emerg("  thread_ack  : %d  <- CPUs NOT yet acked\n",
+		 atomic_read(&msdata->thread_ack));
+	pr_emerg("  inner fn    : %pS\n", msdata->fn);
+	pr_emerg("  active_cpus : %*pbl\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(msdata->active_cpus
+			? msdata->active_cpus : cpu_online_mask));
+}
+
+/**
+ * stopper_print_other_snapshots() - print all non-owner percpu snapshots
+ * @owner_cpu: dump owner CPU -- its slot skipped here (printed in Sec4)
+ *
+ * Reads stopper_snapshot percpu slots written by other CPUs at detection.
+ * Fully sequential -- no IPI, no cross-CPU wait. Bounded time (<1ms).
+ *
+ * A CPU that has not yet reached time_after() will have valid=false.
+ * This is itself diagnostic: shows which CPUs were behind the timeout.
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_print_other_snapshots(unsigned int owner_cpu)
+{
+	unsigned int c;
+
+	pr_emerg("=== Sec6: other CPU snapshots at timeout detection ===\n");
+	pr_emerg("  (each CPU writes its own slot before entering spin)\n");
+
+	for_each_online_cpu(c) {
+		struct stopper_cpu_snapshot *snap;
+		int state;
+
+		if (c == owner_cpu)
+			continue;
+
+		snap = per_cpu_ptr(&stopper_snapshot, c);
+
+		/*
+		 * smp_load_acquire() pairs with smp_store_release() in
+		 * stopper_snapshot_self(). The ACQUIRE semantics guarantee
+		 * that if we observe valid==true, ALL writes to snap->*
+		 * that preceded the smp_store_release() on the writer CPU
+		 * are visible to us before we read any other snap field.
+		 *
+		 * The previous READ_ONCE(valid) + smp_rmb() pattern was
+		 * wrong: smp_rmb() after the load cannot order loads that
+		 * happen after it relative to a store that completed before
+		 * the READ_ONCE -- the barrier was too late.
+		 */
+		if (!smp_load_acquire(&snap->valid)) {
+			pr_emerg("  [CPU%u] not yet detected"
+				 " (behind in loop)\n", c);
+			continue;
+		}
+
+		state = snap->curstate;
+		pr_emerg("  [CPU%u] state=%-11s is_active=%-5s elapsed=~%ums\n",
+			 c, stopper_state_name(state),
+			 snap->is_active ? "YES" : "no",
+			 jiffies_to_msecs(snap->elapsed_j));
+		pr_emerg("         fn=%pS\n", snap->fn);
+		pr_emerg("         caller=%pS\n", (void *)snap->caller);
+	}
+}
+
+/**
+ * stopper_deadlock_dump() - focused dump: owner CPU full + all snapshots
+ * @cpu:       dump-owner CPU (the affected/detecting core)
+ * @msdata:    shared multi_stop_data
+ * @elapsed_j: jiffies elapsed since spin entry on this CPU
+ *
+ * Called ONLY by the one CPU that wins stopper_dump_owner cmpxchg.
+ *
+ * Sec1-5: detailed diagnostics of THIS CPU only (the affected core).
+ * Sec6:   lightweight percpu snapshots from all other CPUs.
+ *
+ * Returns immediately. Caller calls panic().
+ * noinline: keeps migration/N visible at top of ramdump call stack.
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_deadlock_dump(unsigned int cpu,
+					   struct multi_stop_data *msdata,
+					   unsigned long elapsed_j)
+{
+	/* cpu_stopper: fully defined at INSERT POINT B -- safe to use */
+	struct cpu_stopper *st = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper);
+
+	pr_emerg("\n");
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+	pr_emerg("STOPPER DEADLOCK: migration/%u stuck ~%u ms\n"
+		 "Dump owner: CPU%u  |  Others: see Sec6 snapshots\n"
+		 "Cause: nested stop_one_cpu_nowait() re-entrancy\n"
+		 "  active_load_balance_cpu_stop()\n"
+		 "  -> finish_task_switch() -> run_balance_callbacks()\n"
+		 "  -> sched_balance_rq() -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()\n"
+		 "  while already inside stop_two_cpus().\n",
+		 cpu, jiffies_to_msecs(elapsed_j), cpu);
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+
+	/* Sec1: root cause -- which scheduler callback triggered re-entrancy */
+	pr_emerg("=== Sec1: CPU%u outer stopper (root cause) ===\n", cpu);
+	pr_emerg("  outer fn    : %pS\n", st->fn);
+	pr_emerg("  outer caller: %pS\n", (void *)st->caller);
+
+	/* Sec2: state machine snapshot */
+	stopper_dump_msdata(msdata, cpu);
+
+	/* Sec3: CPU masks (cpu_dying_mask=0 confirms LB variant, not hotplug) */
+	pr_emerg("=== Sec3: CPU masks ===\n");
+	pr_emerg("  cpu_online_mask : %*pbl\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(cpu_online_mask));
+	pr_emerg("  cpu_active_mask : %*pbl\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(cpu_active_mask));
+	pr_emerg("  cpu_dying_mask  : %*pbl  (non-zero = hotplug variant)\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(cpu_dying_mask));
+
+	/* Sec4: detailed stopper state of the affected CPU only */
+	pr_emerg("=== Sec4: CPU%u stopper state (detailed) ===\n", cpu);
+	stopper_dump_one_cpu(cpu);
+
+	/* Sec5: full call stack of the affected CPU */
+	pr_emerg("=== Sec5: CPU%u call stack ===\n", cpu);
+	dump_stack();
+
+	/*
+	 * Sec6: lightweight snapshots from every other CPU.
+	 * No IPI. No cross-CPU wait. Owner reads all percpu slots and
+	 * prints them sequentially -- bounded time, clean output.
+	 *
+	 * is_active=YES + state=PREPARE is the definitive deadlock signature.
+	 * state=PREPARE + is_active=no means a non-active spinning CPU.
+	 * "not yet detected" means that CPU was behind in the loop.
+	 */
+	stopper_print_other_snapshots(cpu);
+
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+	pr_emerg("Dump complete. panic() follows immediately.\n"
+		 "Detection: ~3000ms.  Qualcomm bark_time: ~11000ms.\n");
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+}
+
+/* === end INSERT POINT B === */
+
 static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 {
 	struct multi_stop_data *msdata = data;
@@ -209,8 +486,12 @@ static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 	struct multi_stop_data *msdata = data;
 	enum multi_stop_state newstate, curstate = MULTI_STOP_NONE;
 
-	int cpu = smp_processor_id(), err = 0;
+	/*
+	 * FIX: smp_processor_id() returns unsigned int. 'int cpu' is a
+	 * pre-existing mismatch vs cpumask_test_cpu(unsigned int, ...) and
+	 * per_cpu_ptr(..., unsigned int). Clang 19 warns at every call site.
+	 */
+	unsigned int cpu = smp_processor_id();
+	int err = 0, timed_out = 0;
 	const struct cpumask *cpumask;
 	unsigned long flags;
+	unsigned long start_jiffies;
 	bool is_active;
 
@@ -232,6 +513,11 @@ static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 	is_active = cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, cpumask);
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * Snapshot start time before the spin loop.
+	 * Advances via timer tick at HZ=250 in PREPARE state (IRQs ON).
+	 */
+	start_jiffies = jiffies;
+
 	/* Simple state machine */
 	do {
 		/* Chill out and ensure we re-read multi_stop_state. */
@@ -250,9 +536,65 @@ static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 		} else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
 			/*
 			 * At this stage all other CPUs we depend on must spin
-			 * in the same loop. Any reason for hard-lockup should
-			 * be detected and reported on their side.
+			 * in the same loop. Touch the NMI watchdog and
+			 * suppress RCU stall warnings while we spin.
 			 */
 			touch_nmi_watchdog();
-			/* Also suppress RCU CPU stall warnings. */
 			rcu_momentary_eqs();
 		}
+
+		/*
+		 * [FIX-C] Deadlock detection -- position C, unconditional.
+		 *
+		 * PREPARE (IRQs ON -- actual deadlock state):
+		 *   After 3*HZ jiffies (~3000ms at HZ=250): fires.
+		 *   rcu_momentary_eqs() at position B is NOT reached in PREPARE
+		 *   (condition curstate > PREPARE is false), so IRQs stay ON
+		 *   and jiffies advance normally.
+		 *
+		 * DISABLE_IRQ / RUN (IRQs OFF):
+		 *   jiffies frozen -> time_after() always false -> no fire.
+		 *
+		 * FIX: snapshot jiffies ONCE into now_j.
+		 *   Both time_after() and elapsed_j use the same snapshot so
+		 *   they are always consistent. A second read of jiffies for
+		 *   the subtraction could observe a tick increment between
+		 *   the two reads, inflating elapsed_j by one jiffy.
+		 *   Unsigned subtraction (now_j - start_jiffies) is correct
+		 *   even across the 32-bit jiffies wraparound boundary.
+		 *
+		 * FIX: snapshot cpu_stopper fn+caller into locals ONCE.
+		 *   this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper)->fn is read three times in the
+		 *   original code (snapshot, panic string, ... ). Between reads
+		 *   the field could be updated. Snapshot once, use locals
+		 *   everywhere -- consistent diagnostic output, no stale ptr.
+		 *
+		 * TWO-PHASE ACTION:
+		 *   Phase 1 (ALL detecting CPUs, before cmpxchg):
+		 *     stopper_snapshot_self(): write own percpu slot.
+		 *     fn+caller passed as locals -- no re-read of cpu_stopper.
+		 *   Phase 2 (ownership race):
+		 *     SUCCESS -> stopper_deadlock_dump() -> panic().
+		 *     FAILURE -> while(1) cpu_relax() + touch_nmi_watchdog().
+		 *
+		 * timed_out=1 prevents re-entering on future iterations.
+		 */
+		if (!timed_out) {
+			unsigned long now_j = READ_ONCE(jiffies);
+
+			if (time_after(now_j,
+				       start_jiffies + STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES)) {
+				/*
+				 * Snapshot fn and caller from cpu_stopper ONCE.
+				 * Used in Phase 1 (snapshot), Phase 2 (panic
+				 * string), and Sec1 of the dump. A single read
+				 * here prevents any inconsistency if the fields
+				 * are updated between multiple this_cpu_ptr calls.
+				 */
+				struct cpu_stopper *st = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper);
+				void *snap_fn          = READ_ONCE(st->fn);
+				unsigned long snap_caller =
+					READ_ONCE((unsigned long)st->caller);
+				unsigned long elapsed_j = now_j - start_jiffies;
+
+				timed_out = 1;
+
+				/* Phase 1: write own percpu snapshot slot */
+				stopper_snapshot_self(cpu, (int)curstate,
+						      is_active, snap_fn,
+						      snap_caller, elapsed_j);
+
+				/* Phase 2: race for single-CPU dump ownership */
+				if (atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner,
+						   -1, (int)cpu) == -1) {
+					stopper_deadlock_dump(cpu, msdata,
+							      elapsed_j);
+					panic("migration/%u: stuck in "
+					      "multi_cpu_stop for ~%u ms | "
+					      "state=%s thread_ack=%d "
+					      "stop_fn=%pS | nested "
+					      "stop_machine deadlock | "
+					      "see ramdump\n",
+					      cpu,
+					      jiffies_to_msecs(elapsed_j),
+					      stopper_state_names[
+						  min_t(unsigned int,
+							(unsigned int)READ_ONCE(
+							  msdata->state),
+							MULTI_STOP_EXIT)],
+					      atomic_read(&msdata->thread_ack),
+					      snap_fn);
+				}
+
+				/*
+				 * Non-owner path: snapshot already written.
+				 * Spin until owner's panic() resets the system.
+				 * cpu_relax(): ARM64 YIELD hint -- reduces bus
+				 *   pressure, prevents cache-line thrashing that
+				 *   would slow the dump owner's pr_emerg() calls.
+				 * touch_nmi_watchdog(): prevents NMI watchdog
+				 *   firing before owner's panic() completes.
+				 * unreachable(): tells compiler this loop never
+				 *   exits -- suppresses dead-code warnings and
+				 *   prevents emission of unreachable instructions.
+				 */
+				while (1) {
+					cpu_relax();
+					touch_nmi_watchdog();
+				}
+				unreachable();
+			} /* if time_after */
+		} /* if !timed_out */
+
 	} while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);
